item.title: Operator precedence by textual substitution
item.description: Operator precedence is a traditional feature of mathematical notation where, absent explicit parentheses, some operators bind tighter than others ("have higher precedence"). For example, a + b × c would be interpreted as a + (b × c), not as (a + b) × c, because multiplication has higher precedence than addition.
